Offline evaluation metrics 
1. BLEU metrics:
Blue means Bilingual Evaluation Under Study: 
This compares the reference translation what is defined by actual translation with the translation generated by the GenAI system 

 BLEU = BP * exp( SUM_n [
   w_n * log(p_n) ] )
  for n = 1 to N

a. What is BP ( Brevity Penalty):

The Brevity Penalty: It penalizes candidate translations that are too short compared to the reference translations, ensuring that models are encouraged to produce translations that are not just accurate but also sufficiently long and comprehensive.

Example:

Reference: "The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog." (Length r = 9 words)
Candidate 1: "The quick brown fox jumps." (Length c = 5 words)
c <= r, so a penalty applies. r/c = 9/5 = 1.8.

Penalty will be e^(1 - 1.8) = e^(-0.8) ≈ 0.449. This score will be multiplied by the precision.

Candidate 2: "The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog and barks loudly." (Length c = 12 words)
c > r, so the penalty is 1 (no penalty applied).
By applying this penalty, BLEU encourages models to produce translations that are not only accurate in terms of word choice but also have a length comparable to human translations.


b. What is Precision (pn):

An n-gram is a contiguous sequence of 'n' items (words) from a given sample of text.
1-gram (unigram): A single word. E.g., "the", "cat", "sat".
2-gram (bigram): A sequence of two consecutive words. E.g., "the cat", "cat sat", "sat on".
3-gram (trigram): A sequence of three consecutive words. E.g., "the cat sat", "cat sat on".
And so on, up to N-grams (e.g., typically up to 4-grams in standard BLEU calculation).
The BLEU metric calculates precision for various n-gram lengths (e.g., 1-grams, 2-grams, 3-grams, 4-grams) and then combines them.

The Role of N-grams
Before diving into the calculation, it's crucial to understand n-grams:

An n-gram is a contiguous sequence of 'n' items (words) from a given sample of text.
